{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493316"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:05:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:05:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1284"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1284"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.03,0.52,0.06,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1284"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115766"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1284"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1284"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97770"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1238"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4708"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"9663"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4556"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44339"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49305"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115766"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for follow-up of a sexually transmitted infection. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is sexually active with one regular partner of three years duration. They recently stopped using condoms while trying to conceive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination two weeks ago, she appeared well with vital signs within normal limits. High vaginal swab nucleic acid amplification testing (NAAT) and culture were positive for \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E. She was treated with intramuscular ceftriaxone and oral azithromycin. Her partner has been notified and is receiving care.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate test of cure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No test of cure required","Culture in one week","NAAT in two weeks","Serology in six weeks","NAAT in three months"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the Australian STI guidelines, this patient requires follow-up testing after treatment for gonorrhoea. \u003Cstrong\u003ENAAT in two weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is the recommended test of cure after treatment has been completed. This timing allows detection of treatment failure while minimising false positive results from non-viable organisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo test of cure\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as follow-up testing is essential to confirm cure, particularly given the rising rates of antimicrobial resistance in \u003Cem\u003EN. gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECulture in one week\u003C/strong\u003E is too early and less sensitive than NAAT. While culture has the advantage of allowing antimicrobial susceptibility testing, it is not the preferred method for test of cure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerology in six weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is not useful for diagnosis or monitoring of gonorrhoea as antibody tests are neither sensitive nor specific.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENAAT in three months\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for re-screening to detect reinfection, but is too late for a test of cure. After a test of reinfection after three months, ongoing three-monthly screening is recommended for people at ongoing risk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Test of cure for gonorrhoea with NAAT is recommended 2 weeks after treatment to detect treatment failure or reinfection","Partner notification and treatment is essential in gonorrhoea management to prevent reinfection"],"references":["Australian STI Guidelines.\u00a0http://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/gonorrhoea#follow-up. Accessed September 2, 2020.","The Red Book. 6.2 Sexually transmissible infections.\u00a0https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/red-book/communicable-diseases/sexually-transmissible-infections.","Rose SB, Garrett SM, Stanley J, Pullon SRH. Retesting and repeat positivity following diagnosis of Chlamydia trachomatis and Neisseria gonorrhoea in New Zealand: a retrospective cohort study.\u00a0BMC Infect Dis. 2017;17(1):526. Published 2017 Jul 28. doi:10.1186/s12879-017-2635-y","Brocklehurst P (2009) Antibiotics for gonorrhoea in pregnancy.\u00a0Cochrane Database Sys Rev\u00a02002, Issue 2. Art. No.: CD000098. DOI: 10.1002/14651858.CD000098"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97770"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1284"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97770"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-25T10:39:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-25T10:42:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1284"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115766"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https: